<paragraph blockId="37.[151,1436,1175,1472]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[151,225,1247,1272]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Notes.</emphasis>
Both 
<taxonomicName box="[312,441,1247,1271]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="obtusus">
<emphasis box="[312,441,1247,1271]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. obtusus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[515,620,1248,1271]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="poeyi">
<emphasis box="[515,620,1248,1271]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. poeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
are juvenile specimens that conform to 
<taxonomicName box="[1135,1230,1247,1271]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reidi">
<emphasis box="[1135,1230,1247,1271]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. reidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
meristically and morphologically, and are hence synonymised. 
<taxonomicName box="[686,904,1280,1304]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reidi">
<emphasis box="[686,904,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">Hippocampus reidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is thought to be part of the 
<taxonomicName box="[1238,1330,1280,1304]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="kuda">
<emphasis box="[1238,1330,1280,1304]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. kuda</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
complex (
<bibRefCitation author="Teske" box="[158,358,1314,1339]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refString="Teske, P. R., Hamilton, H., Palsboll, P. J., Choo, C. K., Gabr, H., Lourie, S. A., Santos, M., Sreepada, R. A., Cherry, M. I. &amp; Matthee, C. A. (2005) Molecular evidence for long-distance colonization in an Indo-Pacific seahorse lineage. Marine Ecology Progress Series, 286, 249 - 260. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.3354 / meps 286249" type="journal article" year="2005">
Teske 
<emphasis box="[233,290,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">et al.</emphasis>
2005
</bibRefCitation>
), and is very closely related to 
<taxonomicName box="[712,847,1314,1338]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="algiricus">
<emphasis box="[712,847,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. algiricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Casey" box="[862,1064,1314,1338]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refString="Casey, S. P., Hall, H. J., Stanley, H. F. &amp; Vincent, A. C. J. (2004) The origin and evolution of seahorses (genus Hippocampus): a phylogenetic study using the cytochrome b gene of mitochondrial DNA. Molecular Phylogenetics and Evolution, 30, 261 - 272. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.1016 / j. ympev. 2003.08.018" type="journal article" year="2004">
Casey 
<emphasis box="[940,998,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">et al.</emphasis>
2004
</bibRefCitation>
; 
<bibRefCitation author="Silveira" box="[1077,1295,1314,1339]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" refString="Silveira, R. B., Siccha-Ramirez, R., Silva, J. R. S. &amp; Oliveira, C. (2014) Morphological and molecular evidence for the occurrence of three Hippocampus species (Teleostei: Syngnathidae) in Brazil. Zootaxa, 3861 (4), 317 - 32. http: // dx. doi. org / 10.11646 / zootaxa. 3861.4.2" type="journal article" year="2014">
Silveira 
<emphasis box="[1172,1230,1314,1338]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">et al.</emphasis>
2014
</bibRefCitation>
). Indeed the Barcode of Life places them both in the same BIN group, with an average within-group divergence of 1.28% (
<collectionCode box="[158,236,1381,1405]" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">BOLD</collectionCode>
2016). Research is needed to determine whether gene flow across the Atlantic Ocean takes place between 
<taxonomicName box="[151,239,1414,1438]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="reidi">
<emphasis box="[151,239,1414,1438]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. reidi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[297,433,1414,1438]" class="Actinopterygii" family="Syngnathidae" genus="Hippocampus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Syngnathiformes" pageId="37" pageNumber="38" phylum="Chordata" rank="species" species="algiricus">
<emphasis box="[297,433,1414,1438]" italics="true" pageId="37" pageNumber="38">H. algiricus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, but we retain them both as valid species here due to the large geographic distance and entire ocean basin between the two populations.
</paragraph>
